03531nam a22005175i 9780300168723DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20102010ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001687237 a10.12987/97803001687232doi  a(DE-B1597)485665  a(OCoLC)793206891  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 7aLIT0000002bisacsh1 ade Vega, Lope, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFuenteovejuna /cLope de Vega. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Margellos World Republic of Letters00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- tCHARACTERS -- tACT I -- tACT II -- tACT III -- tNOTES -- tWORKS CITED AND RECOMMENDED0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLope de Vega "single-handedly created the Spanish national theatre," writes Roberto González Echevarría in the introduction to this new translation of Fuenteovejuna. Often compared to Shakespeare, Molière, and Racine, Lope is widely considered the greatest of all Spanish playwrights, and Fuenteovejuna (The Sheep Well) is among the most important Spanish Golden Age plays.Written in 1614, Fuenteovejuna centers on the decision of an entire village to admit to the premeditated murder of a tyrannical ruler. Lope masterfully employs the tragicomic conventions of the Spanish comedia as he leavens the central dilemma of the peasant lovers, Laurencia and Frondoso, with the shenanigans of Mengo, the gracioso or clown. Based on an actual historical incident, Fuenteovejuna offers a paean to collective responsibility and affirmation of the timeless values of justice and kindness.Translator G. J. Racz preserves the nuanced voice and structure of Lope de Vega's text in this first English translation in analogical meter and rhyme. Roberto González Echevarría surveys the history of Fuenteovejuna, as well as Lope's enormous literary output and indelible cultural imprint. Racz's compelling translation and González Echevarría's rich framework bring this timeless Golden Age drama alive for a new generation of readers and performers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aGonzález Echevarría, Roberto1 aRacz, G. J.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300168723423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300168723.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles